  "doc_id": "37449",
  "text": "The lifetime scalability results are similar to throughput scalability. On average, WCP+WQB reduces the WBPKI for 2-, 4-, 8-, and 16-core systems by 46%, 49%, 49%, and 47% over UCP, respectively (the graphs are not included for brevity). These results show that our techniques are scalable. PCM has been proposed as a candidate for main memory systems by many researchers [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . [CITATION_6] successfully mitigate the negative impacts of PCM's long latencies, high energy, and finite endurance by using area-neutral buffer organizations and applying partial writes technique. [CITATION_7] propose a hybrid architecture that uses a DRAM cache to filter accesses to PCM. Such an anchitecture has the latency benefits of DRAM and the capacity and scalability benefits of PCM. [CITATION_8] study the page partitioning in the DRAM cache to reduce the amount of data written back to PCM. [CITATION_9] propose PCM as a direct replacement for DRAM in main memory without buffer organization. Zhang et al.",
